When testing the markdown module

`npm install markdown`

`browserify -r markdown > bundle.js`

It appears to render the correct code, but if you execute the following code it will error:
    var input = "# Heading\n\nParagraph";
    var output = require( "markdown" ).markdown.toHTML( input );

It turns out that the module imports a module in it's own package of the same name "markdown"

```
exports.markdown = require("./markdown");
exports.parse = exports.markdown.toHTML;
```

However this isn't evaluated, instead the code require requires itself and the objects structure gets messed up after this.

I have 2 files `a.js` and `b.js`, `b.js` is empty, `a.js` only contains `var b = require( './b' )`.

If I run browserify in watch mode, the bundle is OK. But since 1.14.4, if I modify `b.js` (for example if I add an empty line), then `b.js` is included twice and required by default, as if it was an entry file.

My bundle ends like that:

```
// [...]

require.define("/b.js",function(require,module,exports,__dirname,__filename,process){});

require.define("/a.js",function(require,module,exports,__dirname,__filename,process){var b = require( './b' );
});
require("/a.js");

require.define("/b.js",function(require,module,exports,__dirname,__filename,process){
});
require("/b.js");
})();
```

Is there a simple way to get run-time values from the node.js host into the browserify bundle without generating an intermediate file on disk?  For example, say I want to generate a bundle that makes an ajax call to a particular URL, but I don't want to hard code the URL in the source file.  What is the best way to get that information into the bundle without polluting the global namespace?

Something like this seems to work, but I can't find it documented anywhere, and I don't know if it will continue to be supported:

var url = 'http://my.url/';
builder.addEntry('startup',{body:startup.toString()+'\nstartup(\''+url+'\');'});

function startup(url) {
  var client = require('./client');
  client.start(url);
}

If you were to make a single-line comment on the last line of one of the scripts in your bundle, you'll notice browserify.js giving you a syntax error once the bundle has been loading into the page. I think this is because of the fact that browserify wraps each script in a closure, but it doesn't do this with new-lines. So you're script:

```
// code
// Last line comment
```

Becomes something like this:

```
require.define("/public/scripts/myscript.js",function(require,module,exports,__dirname,__filename,process){//code
// Last line comment});
```

The code generated by browserify is commented out because there is no new-line character after the last line in the script. This breaks the bundle, and I've ran into this issue twice.

Fixing this is simple, just append a new-line character to each script, or prepend a new-line to the browserify's ending `});`..same difference.

For compatibility reasons the module object provided by browserify should equal node's. I've added some properties that made sense to me and omitted those, that seemed to be deprecated/weird/unused (e.g. the empty children-array). 

The module has now these properties:

``` javascript
        var module_ = {
            id : filename,
            filename: filename,
            exports : {},
            loaded : false,
            // stores a reference to the module that
            // required this module for the first time
            parent: null  
        };
```

In order to add `parent` I have to resolve the full module path of the required module (https://github.com/jhnns/node-browserify/commit/4c7a4ad0cf7eb6ba74f9fa4248dc47a8c575f7f8), which may have an impact on performance. Unfortunately I couldn't find a quick solution for this.

What do you think?

another response to #132

`require` only takes a single argument, 
so what if supplying a second argument was a directive to browserify?

this would give us the desired configurability, and the advantage over #174 
is that the configuration would fall in front of you eyes, not off in a file where you 
would forget about it. 

``` js

//load './client' when bundling for client side.
var server       = require('./server', './client')   

//ignore './server-only' when bundling for client side
var onlyServer = require('./server-only', null) 

```

I'm not sure how everyone feels about adding a second argument, but I think, all things considered,
this might be the cleanest, easiest to use method.

@isaacs has stated that the module system is "finished", and I think he's pretty serious, 
so it's unlikely that it would suddenly start behaving differently with a second argument.

